That's RU exhaustion, and the SDK already retried internally (9 times by default) before surfacing it — so it's sustained throttling, not a momentary spike.

Almost certainly ledgerEntries, and GetBalanceAsync is why. Every debit reads every entry ever written for that ledger and sums them client-side. 
With ~12,000+ entries from your runs, one balance check materializes and transfers all of them — easily 100+ RU per call. At 30 TPS that's 3,000+ RU/s from balance reads alone, 
and it grows with every payment you post. Confirm in the metrics blade: Total Requests split by container, filtered to 429.

The compounding problem: it's all one logical partition. ledgerEntries is partitioned by ledgerId, and your entire load test hits a single ledger. 
A logical partition is served by one physical partition, capped around 10,000 RU/s — so provisioning more throughput past that point does nothing for this workload. You'd be buying RU that other partitions can use and yours can't.

This cuts RU substantially — no document materialization, no network transfer of 12,000 records — 
but it still scans every entry. It buys you an order of magnitude, not immunity. 
The durable fix is a periodic checkpoint entry (a snapshot row with the running total) so balance reads only sum entries since the last checkpoint.

One caveat on that query. Your ledger doc stores createdAt as ...+00:00 while the entry stores ...Z. 
Cosmos compares these lexicographically as strings, and those two formats don't sort consistently against each other. 
If entries were ever written with mixed formats, the <= @at filter will silently drop some. 
Worth running a quick SELECT DISTINCT sanity check on the format before trusting the result — and note the existing LINQ version has the identical exposure, so this isn't a regression, just newly visible.

What the 429 does to your pipeline right now: a CosmosException isn't TabaPayProcessingException or HttpRequestException, 
so in HandlePaymentOutcome it falls to the generic catch → abandon → redelivery. That redelivery re-reads the doc and re-patches, adding more Cosmos load, which causes more 429s. 
Under sustained throttling that's a feedback loop, and messages eventually DLQ after maxDeliveryCount for what's really a capacity problem. Worth checking your DLQ for a cluster of these.

For getting a clean run in the meantime: point the load test at a fresh ledger with zero entries. 
Your current one carries the accumulated cost of every prior run, so each test is slower and more expensive than the last — and that alone may put you back under the limit without touching provisioning.

